<strong>The Wooden Hive — permanent beekeeping</strong>

The white Catherby hive, rebuilt proper. A tall three-part apiary: harvest never destroys it, and the colony never turns on you.

<strong>Construction</strong>
Craft the three sections — Hive Stand, Hive Body, Hive Roof — and stack them in a 1×3 column: stand, body, roof. The moment the column is complete the hive assembles itself, entrance facing you.

<strong>Seeding</strong>
Right-click the empty hive with a populated reed or papyrus skep. The colony transplants in; the woven skep is handed back empty.

<strong>Harvest</strong>
Only with the <a href="apiaryscoop">apiary scoop</a>. When the combs hang heavy, scoop out 3–6 honeycombs plus a scrape of beeswax — roughly weekly. Bare hands and other tools are refused; the combs stay put until you bring the scoop.

<strong>Flower gate</strong>
Bees need 3+ bee-feed plants within 8 blocks. More flowers = faster combs. Block info shows the flower count and time remaining.

<strong>Winter truth</strong>
• At freezing, production stalls — the colony clusters for warmth and waits.
• In deep cold (−10°C), the batch is lost and the timer resets.
• A sealed glass-roofed room buys +5°C. Physics, no exceptions.

<strong>Propagation</strong>
A settled colony with 6+ flowers nearby swarms into nearby empty skeps every couple of days. A permanent, tamed source of bees — it never hostile-swarms.

<strong>Legacy</strong>
Skeps built before the rework still work. The new hives just stand taller.

'Bee' good.
